<collectionCode box="[1109,1147,1346,1367]" country="USA" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15556" name="William and Lynda Steere Herbarium of the New York Botanical Garden" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="Herbarium">NY</collectionCode>
). Scale bars: 
<collectionCode box="[1269,1288,1346,1367]" country="USA" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15406" name="Harvard University - Arnold Arboretum" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="Herbarium">A</collectionCode>
, 
<collectionCode box="[1298,1314,1346,1367]" country="Germany" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15534" name="Botanischer Garten und Botanisches Museum Berlin-Dahlem, Zentraleinrichtung der Freien Universitaet" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="Herbarium">B</collectionCode>
= 100 μm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,1414,2089]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,519,1414,1440]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Distribution and habitat:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. S. Fernandes &amp; Salino" authorityYear="2014" box="[519,784,1414,1440]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis box="[519,784,1414,1440]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Meniscium triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[1064,1112,1415,1441]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">type</typeStatus>
locality in 
<collectingCountry box="[1241,1351,1414,1440]" name="Colombia" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Colombia</collectingCountry>
where it grows in secondary forest at 
<quantity box="[459,547,1450,1477]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.315" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="m" value="1315.0">1315 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="7" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,1414,2089]" box="[189,891,1486,1513]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,356,1486,1512]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Etymology:—</emphasis>
The epithet refers to the shape of lateral pinnae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,1414,2089]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,294,1522,1548]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Notes:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. S. Fernandes &amp; Salino" authorityYear="2014" box="[294,557,1522,1548]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis box="[294,557,1522,1548]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Meniscium triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is well characterized by features that have not been commonly mentioned in the past, such as the presence of scales on the abaxial surface of the lamina (Fig. 2D). The species is also distinguished by the presence of the buds on axils of distal pinnae (Fig. 2A), a character that is also found in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. S. Fernandes &amp; Salino" baseAuthorityName="Smith &amp; Lellinger" baseAuthorityYear="1985" box="[1170,1328,1594,1620]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cocleanum">
<emphasis box="[1170,1328,1594,1620]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. cocleanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. S. Fernandes &amp; Salino" baseAuthorityName="Smith &amp; Lellinger" baseAuthorityYear="1985" box="[136,295,1630,1656]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cocleanum">
<emphasis box="[136,295,1630,1656]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. cocleanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a glabrous abaxial laminar surface, oblong sori, and glabrous sporangia, while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. S. Fernandes &amp; Salino" authorityYear="2014" box="[1235,1407,1630,1656]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis box="[1235,1407,1630,1656]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has scales and appressed trichomes on the main veins and costae, round sori and glandular sporangia (Fig. 3B).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,1414,2089]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. S. Fernandes &amp; Salino" authorityYear="2014" box="[136,401,1702,1728]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis box="[136,401,1702,1728]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Meniscium triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Swartz" authorityYear="1803" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus 1759:" baseAuthorityYear="1325" box="[458,625,1702,1728]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reticulatum">
<emphasis box="[458,625,1702,1728]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. reticulatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the same triangular–lanceolate pinna outline. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. S. Fernandes &amp; Salino" authorityYear="2014" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Meniscium triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by having buds in the axils of distal pinnae, abaxial surface of costae and veins tomentose with trichomes and scales, trichomes 
<quantity box="[689,826,1774,1801]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="mm" value="0.4" valueMax="0.5" valueMin="0.3">0.3–0.5 mm</quantity>
long, acicular, ciliform, dense, appressed, which gives a white aspect to the costae; conspicuous scales 0.4–1.4 × 
<quantity box="[796,962,1810,1837]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="mm" value="0.075" valueMax="0.1" valueMin="0.05">0.05–0.10 mm</quantity>
, appressed, caducous, with irregular forms, with long-ciliate margin, sori rounded (Fig. 2A–D), and sporangia capsule with globose, caducous glands (Fig. 3B). Conversely, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Swartz" authorityYear="1803" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus 1759:" baseAuthorityYear="1325" box="[275,440,1882,1908]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reticulatum">
<emphasis box="[275,440,1882,1908]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. reticulatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks buds on the axils of basal pinnae or buds, has the abaxial surface of costae and veins with curved, acicular trichomes, 
<quantity box="[500,634,1918,1945]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="mm" value="0.15" valueMax="0.2" valueMin="0.1">0.1–0.2 mm</quantity>
long, slightly to moderately dense, scales usually lacking or rare, filiform or shapeless and margin not ciliate, sori oblong, and sporangia glabrous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,1414,2089]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pichi Sermolli" authorityYear="1968" baseAuthorityName="Mettenius" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[189,501,1990,2016]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="membranaceum">
<emphasis box="[189,501,1990,2016]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Meniscium membranaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an indument of trichomes and scales on costae and veins similar to that of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. S. Fernandes &amp; Salino" authorityYear="2014" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="triangularis">M. triangularis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
from which it differs by having only 2–4 pinnae pairs, with 19–20 areole rows between costa and pinna margin, buds in the axils of basal pinnae and straight secondary veins forming a 180° angle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[136,1452,1804,1898]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,229,1804,1826]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">FIGURE</emphasis>
. Scanning electron micrograph (SEM) of spores. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[721,738,1804,1825]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">A</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[749,765,1804,1825]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">B</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. S. Fernandes &amp; Salino" baseAuthorityName="Smith &amp; Lellinger" baseAuthorityYear="1985" box="[778,992,1804,1826]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cocleanum">
<emphasis box="[778,992,1804,1826]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Meniscium cocleanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spores with winged surface. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1269,1286,1804,1826]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">C</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1298,1315,1804,1825]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">D</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. S. Fernandes &amp; Salino" authorityYear="2014" box="[1328,1451,1804,1826]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="divergens">
<emphasis box="[1328,1451,1804,1826]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">M. divergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with echinulate surface with low, dense echinulae. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[635,651,1840,1861]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">E</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[664,679,1840,1861]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">F</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jermy &amp; Walker" authorityYear="1985" baseAuthorityName="Maxon &amp; Morton" baseAuthorityYear="1938" box="[693,830,1841,1862]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nesioticum">
<emphasis box="[693,830,1841,1862]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">M. nesioticum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with cristate-reticulate surface. (A–B from 
<emphasis box="[1260,1452,1840,1862]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Salino et al. 15361,</emphasis>
BHCB; C–D from 
<emphasis box="[318,548,1876,1898]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">T.W. Henkel et al. 4368,</emphasis>
NY; E–F from 
<emphasis box="[697,882,1876,1898]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">G.C. Aymard 5331,</emphasis>
UC). Scale bars: A, C, E = 10 µm; B, D, F = 5 µm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[136,1451,1945,2043]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pichi Sermolli" authorityYear="1968" baseAuthorityName="Mettenius" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[189,503,1945,1971]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="membranaceum">
<emphasis box="[189,503,1945,1971]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Meniscium membranaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. S. Fernandes &amp; Salino" authorityYear="2014" box="[565,741,1945,1971]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis box="[565,741,1945,1971]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">M. triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have echinulate spores, however, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. S. Fernandes &amp; Salino" authorityYear="2014" box="[1146,1322,1945,1971]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis box="[1146,1322,1945,1971]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">M. triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has sparse stelae forming clumps (Fig. 5C–D), while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pichi Sermolli" authorityYear="1968" baseAuthorityName="Mettenius" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[624,842,1981,2007]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="membranaceum">
<emphasis box="[624,842,1981,2007]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">M. membranaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has stelae with perforations (Fig. 5A–B). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Swartz" authorityYear="1803" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus 1759:" baseAuthorityYear="1325" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Meniscium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reticulatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Meniscium reticulatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has cristate–reticulate spores, confirming the statements of 
<bibRefCitation author="Wood, C. C." box="[935,1082,2017,2043]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="191 - 202" refId="ref8131" refString="Wood, C. C. (1973) Spore variation in the Thelypteridaceae. Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society 67 (1): 191 - 202." type="journal article" year="1973">Wood (1973)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Tryon, R. M. &amp; Tryon, A. F." box="[1136,1391,2017,2043]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" refId="ref8048" refString="Tryon, R. M. &amp; Tryon, A. F. (1982) Fern and allied plants, with special reference to Tropical America. Springer Verlag, New York, 857 pp. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 1 - 4613 - 8162 - 4" type="book" year="1982">Tryon &amp; Tryon (1982)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
